Webhooks - External Authorization Check

Simple Meaning
When a request comes to Kubernetes, instead of deciding internally, Kubernetes asks an external server: "Should I allow this request or not?"

Two Types of Webhooks
Type	              What It Does
Validating Webhook	Only checks if request is allowed. Cannot modify.
Mutating Webhook	  Can modify the request before processing.

Example Use Case
You write a custom policy: "If pod image is not from approved registry, reject it."

When someone tries to create a pod, Kubernetes asks your webhook server. Your server checks the image and replies Allow or Reject.

Real Benefit for IT Working
RBAC is good for standard permissions
Webhooks give you full control
You can integrate with your company's existing approval systems
No need to change Kubernetes core code

Authorization Methods Comparison
Method	  Basis	          Usage	         Complexity
RBAC	    Role	          Most common	   Simple
ABAC	    Attributes	    Rare	         Complex
Webhook	  External server	Advanced cases	Custom

Complete Flow
Request Arrives → Authentication → Authorization (RBAC/ABAC/Webhook) → Admission Controller → Resource Created

Final Short Note
RBAC does most of the authorization work in Kubernetes
Use Webhooks when you need advanced or custom rules
ABAC is rarely used because it is too complex to manage
